<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>EA Committee: Written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold"> submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">National Trust</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">National Trust is a major landowner in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> with 255,000 h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">res (ha) of countryside, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">700 k</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ilo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">etres</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> of coastline and 400 gardens in our care for the benefit of the nation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">2. Approximately half </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">of this land is of h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">igh nature value, accessible and  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> enjoyed by million</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">s of people. Together with tenanted farmland, it makes a significant contribution to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">and regional </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">economies. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">3. We recognise the harm caused by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Invasive Non-Native Species (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">IN</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">NS) - be they plant diseases in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> gardens</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and woodlands, plants in water bodies or predatory mammals on seabird </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">islands. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">4. We recognise the value of both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">effective quarantine measures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and rapid reaction to control and eradicate INNS inclu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ding plant diseases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> O</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ur </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">staff can spend up to half of their time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> controlling invasive species</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> at a cost of up to £12000 per h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">a depending on the situation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">5. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The draft EU Directive proposal to list 50 INNS is not sufficiently sensitive to existing risk from species and those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">native species </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">that are poise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> to cause harm in areas </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">of the EU where they are not native. More emphasis should be based on risk-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">base</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">d assessments that identify species </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">of most </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">concern and provide the basis for risk-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">based trading.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">6. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The Invasive Non-Native</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Species Framework Strategy</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">for Great Britain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> (GB INNS Framework), </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">promoting sound </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> of INNS, could help define what success looks like, promote more effective engagement with NGOs, and forge more citizen science and state agency based partnerships.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">7. The Scottish INNS legislation looks promising, as do initiatives in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Republic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> to tackle INNS on an island –wide basis. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">1.1.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The National Trust welcomes the opportunity to provide evidence to the Environmental Audit Committee’s inquiry on Invasive Species.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">1.2. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The National Trust is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Europe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">’s largest conservation charity with over 4 million members and an annual turnover of more than £430 million. We currently manage over 250,000 ha of countryside, several hundred historic houses, gardens and parks and more than 700 km of coastline across </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. Nearly 50 % of the water in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> runs through National Trust land.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">1.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The National Trust exists to look after special places for ever, for everyone. We do this in a way which connects </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> benefits </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">of nature </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">with people, welcoming around 100 million visits to the outdoors, coast and countryside locations managed by the National Trust. We invest over £130m into conservation projects each year, and some of this funding comes from corporate partners. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">1.4. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Management of invasive species is a major investment in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">resource</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> for the Trust. Typically our countryside a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">nd gardens staff spend up to half </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">of their time reducing the impacts of invasive species and plant diseases, most of which are non-native.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">1.5 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We welcome the Committee’s interest in the degree to which the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> should align with EU initiatives, look to legislation in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> as a guide, and help shape the G</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">B INNS Framework of the future.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Overview</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">2.1 Invasive Non Native Species (INN</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> are a major threat to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">’s native wildlife and its economy. They also have adverse societal impacts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">which include the profound sense of loss of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> iconic and beautiful native species such as the red squirrel </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(which can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">cont</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">act and die from disease spread by the non-native grey squirrel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">2.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Programmes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">to tackle INNS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">in which we are especially active, often in partnership with other organisations and with the help of hundreds of volunteers, include: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(1)  Control of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Hottentot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> fig from coastal slopes in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Cornwall</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">to win back flower rich grassland and restore feeding places for the recently re-established chough, the county’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">emblemic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> bird</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(2) Control of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">Rhododendron</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> in north </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Wales</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and north Devon to restore oak woodland, and its native bird and lichen species</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, and on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Brownsea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Lundy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Islands</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, to restore habitat for the red squirrel and Lundy cabbage respectively. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(3) Eradication of rats from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Lundy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Island</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> to save </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">species such as the Manx shearwater </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">from extinction there</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">) Control of grey squirrels in and around refuge areas for red squirrels in the north of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Anglesey</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">) Control of non-native aquatic (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">New Zealand</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> pygmy weed) and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">bankside</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> plants (such as Japanese knotweed and Himalayan balsam) in and around our thousands of ponds and other water bodies </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">) Plant health and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">biosecurity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> in our heritage gardens. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We have a rigour programme of deploying </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">biosecurity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> to minimise the risk of plant diseases damaging high value plants and destroying the beauty of our nationally important gardens.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Rigorous prioritisation based on risk</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> assessment is critical</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. Early intervention and the resources need</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ed for this are equally </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">critical, especially where non-native invasive species have been tracked and found to be established in satellite areas. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Our concerns</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">future of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">Defra GB INNS Programme Board</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The GB INNS Programme Board represents an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">important commitment by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> to reduce the damaging influence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> of non-native species</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, and it should be maintained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. But it nee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ds more resource to engage with people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">to be vigilant, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">exert stricter quarantine measures, control and eradicate some species at an appropriate scale, define success and report on success or failure.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> The Board also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">needs to prioritise high risk species – these are the small suite of non-native invasive species that have the highest capacity to transform </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">native </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">habitats and ecosystems. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> In some cases the Board needs to stimulate research where there are significant knowledge gaps. The two examples below illustrate the need to act now on (1) a high risk species not yet established in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">; and (2) on one which is established but spreading and whose ecological impact is not well understood.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(1) Water hyacinth, native to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">South America</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, is a major pest of water bodies, making them </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">unnavigable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and reducing their biodiversity. This species does not breed in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> yet, but could do so in a series of warmer weather years. We need a formal watching brief backed by a rapid response mechanism to ensure that water hyacinth does not become established in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(2) Chinese water deer, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">established in the east of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, has recently invaded </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Orford</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> Ness</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, a 15 km long shingle spit off the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Suffolk</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> coast that is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">internationally important fo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">r its wildlife and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">historical heritag</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">e. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We do not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">know </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">the impact of Chinese water deer on either the natural or cultural or historical features on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Orford</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> Ness</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> but remain concerned about this knowledge gap.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.2 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">Objective setting and realistic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">costings</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> for control/eradication of INNS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">In the management of INNS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">success</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> is reported in a variety of ways</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. It is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">sufficient for success to be gauged by how much </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">of a INNS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> has been removed. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">A better measure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">is if native species and habi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">tats can be shown to have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">been restored</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, or ecosystem functioning improved</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> as a result of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We should not be afraid to recognise failure but need to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">make sure effective communication is in place to report </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">what does not work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">Increasing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">use of innovative </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">methods </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">detect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> early stages of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">establishment of INNS. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Government and others should make more use of innovative methods to detect the early stage of INNS establishment where these are practicable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">For example, hair tubes for mammals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">and collections of faeces </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">from which DNA can be extracted to identify species and also individuals; e (environmental) DNA – which can be used to track presence of non-native invasive amphibians such as bullfrogs in ponds for example; camera</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> traps. Much of the data collection can be done by volunteers but would need coordinating with state agencies and analysing by scientists.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.4 T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">he minimum requirements for successful management </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">of INNS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The National Trust</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> sees the minimum requirements for successful management of INNS as:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">3.4.1 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Realistic and appropriate prioritisation based on risk assessment for native wildlife, people and the economy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. This could lead to risk-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">based trading of species such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">INNS of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">aquatic plants</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">3.4.2 Consultation with local people leading to r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">apid decision making leading to rapid action</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">3.4.3 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Action at the appropriate scale (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">bankside</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> INNS plants such as Japanese knotweed,  whole water </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">catchments rather than</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> just one </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">part of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">catchment where the species is known and conspicuous</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">3.4.4 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Criteria for success agreed early in the project</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, and success/failure reported on at milestones and at the end of the project.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.5 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">Delivery mechanisms</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We see a m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ajor role for Local Nature Partnerships </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">as delivery bodies </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">to coordinate, communicate and stimulate state agency, local authority and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">volunteer partnerships to tackle INNS</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.6 Legislation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We advocate b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">etter use of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> powers in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">W</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ildlife </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&amp; C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ountryside</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> Act 1981 Schedu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">le 9 and equivalent in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Northern Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> to raise awareness of the risks of unrestricted movement of certain species by human agency, and also learning from INNS legislation in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.7 Knowledge gaps</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We advocate m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ore research on ecological processes and pathogens transfer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> between INNS and native species </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">non-native and native crayfish species;  grey/red squirrel - </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">NT supporting the latter)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3.8 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The Committee might want to consider the following</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.8.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">1. Is the EU draft Directive on Invasive Non – Native Species (INNS) fit for purpose? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">the EU draft Directive’s s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">election of 50 species deemed to cause most</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> harm</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> sufficiently sensitive –</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> would a risk-based</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">selection</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, using </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">climate change scenario</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">s and/or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">horizon scanning be better at preventing spread</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">establishment?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Will the EU Directive be sufficiently sensitive to th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">e need to p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">revent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> spread of potentially invasive species from EU Member states where </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">they are either </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">native</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">long established to those where not yet established but where they could cause harm.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.8.2. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> How do we prioritise (we cannot manage all INNS everywhere)? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">We should focus on s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">trengthen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> existing legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> Scottish model looks promising.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">cological priorities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> should be based</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> on global responsibilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, for example the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> removal of rats from seabird islands. Societal and economic benefits from managing INNS may</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> however need to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> be based on different priorities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, for instance </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">keeping new plant diseases out of publicly accessible heritage gardens, and clearing away Himalayan balsam to allow access to river banks by anglers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.8.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3. How do we measure and report on success and failure? What does success look like?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Management needs to be lead by carefully constructed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">smart</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> objectives. INNS </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">can be regarded as successfully managed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> when they have been prevented from invading the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> through effective legislation and/or quarantine. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">In some cases </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">invading or established INNS may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">have been controlled successfully </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">but the expected positive impacts such as evident restoration of native species and/or habitats</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> or wider </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">societal or economic benefit may not have been measured. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">The f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">ailure of management of INNS is rarely reported</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">. This may be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> because objectives were poorly defined at the outset.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">A s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">trengthened GB INNS Framework Strategy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">could help to address this problem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">, especially if</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> more inclusive of NGOs in decision making</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> includ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">es</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> on appropriate application of the precautionary principle.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">3.8.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">4. Should there be a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> UK/all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic"> approach to management of INNS?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">INNSs do not respect international boundaries, especially when there is no sea barrier or obvious border control. It makes sense to support the strengthening of al </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">/ all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Ireland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt"> strategy to tackle INNS. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Again a strengthened GB INNS Framework Strat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">egy has a supporting role here, as it does in promoting functional working links between Departments at state borders.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">27 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>